        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "If your property has a regulated pool, you must either provide the buyer with a current pool safety certificate before settlement, or provide a Form 36 (notice of no pool safety certificate) which gives the buyer 90 days from settlement to obtain one. Under the Building Act 1975 (Qld), providing neither is not an option. Most sellers are better served by obtaining the certificate before sale, as providing a Form 36 can create a perception of compliance risk that gives buyers a reason to negotiate the price downward."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is a Form 36 and how does it affect my property sale in Queensland?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A Form 36 is a notice of no pool safety certificate provided by the seller to the buyer at the time of contract. It informs the buyer that the pool does not have a current safety certificate and gives the buyer 90 days from settlement to obtain one at their expense. Buyers who receive a Form 36 know they are taking on a compliance cost and unknown rectification work. This can cause some buyers to negotiate a discount or withdraw from the purchase. Sellers who provide a current pool safety certificate avoid this uncertainty entirely."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How much does a pool safety certificate cost in Brisbane?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A pool safety inspection by a licensed pool safety inspector in Brisbane typically costs between $150 and $350 depending on the inspector and the pool type. If the inspection reveals non-compliant features that need rectification before the certificate can be issued, the cost of those rectifications is additional. Common items that require work include pool fence height, latch and hinge compliance, self-closing gate mechanisms, and non-compliant resuscitation signage. Getting an inspection early in your listing preparation gives you time to address any compliance issues without the pressure of a pending settlement."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How long is a pool safety certificate valid for in Queensland?",
