        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A pool safety certificate in Queensland is valid for two years for non-shared pools (a pool on a single residential lot used only by residents of that lot). It is valid for one year for shared pools. The certificate must be current at the time it is provided to the buyer. If your certificate expired before the sale, you will need a new inspection before the certificate can be provided."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What happens if I sell a Queensland property with a pool and don't comply with the pool safety rules?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Under the Building Act 1975 (Qld), a failure to provide either a pool safety certificate or a Form 36 at the time of contract is a breach of the Act. Penalties can apply. Beyond the regulatory consequence, a buyer who discovers after contract that pool safety compliance has not been handled correctly may have grounds to raise issues before settlement. The compliant approach is straightforward: get the pool inspected, address any issues, and provide the certificate or Form 36 before contract."
      }
    }
